The best approach is **`System.IO.Abstractions`** — a battle-tested NuGet package that wraps the entire `System.IO` surface behind injectable interfaces. No need to write custom wrappers.

### 1. Install the packages

```bash
dotnet add <YourProject> package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
// Program.cs or Startup.cs
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
public class ConfigManager(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool EnsureDirectory(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});
// MockFileSystem includes directories automatically for existing files

var manager = new ConfigManager(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", manager.Load("/config.json"));

manager.Save("/out.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/out.txt"));
```

**Why this over a custom wrapper?**

| | Custom wrapper | `System.IO.Abstractions` |
|---|---|---|
| Coverage | Only methods you wrap | Full `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, `Stream`, etc. |
| Maintenance | You maintain it | Community-maintained, well-tested |
| Test helpers | You write your own mock | `MockFileSystem` included, handles path normalization |

Once installed, use the `detect-static-dependencies` and `migrate-static-to-wrapper` skills (just ask!) to mechanically find and replace all `File.*` / `Directory.*` call sites across your codebase.
